||Murray Reynolds || {{nts|16}}&nbsp;feet<br> (4.9&nbsp;m) || 1,447&nbsp;feet<br> (441&nbsp;m)<ref>{{cite web | work = [[Geographic Names Information System]] | publisher = [[United States Geological Survey]] | date = September 1, 1989 | url ={{Gnis3|1201536}} | title = Murray Reynolds Falls | accessdate = November 17, 2009 }}</ref> || {{coord|41|19|06|N|76|16|26|W|name=Murray Reynolds Falls}} || chute || G. Murray Reynolds (1838<U+2013>1904) was a colonel, politician, and a brother of Elizabeth Reynolds Ricketts, wife of R. B. Ricketts.<ref name="autogenerated1">{{cite journal | title = Death of Col. G. Murray Reynolds | journal = The Historical Record of Wyoming Valley. A Compilation of Matters of Local History from the Columns of the Wilkes-Barre Record |editor = Johnson, F.C. | location = [[Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania]] | publisher = Press of the Wilkes-Barre Record | year = 1905 | volume = XIII | pages = 139<U+2013>142 | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=uxUUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA141&dq=colonel+murray+reynolds#v=onepage&q=colonel%20murray%20reynolds&f=false | accessdate = November 20, 2009 }}</ref> Murray Reynolds Falls was once known as "Pulpit Falls" for the [[pulpit]] shaped rock in the midst of the chute.<ref name= "endless">Mitchell, pp. 44<U+2013>47.</ref> It is 1.3&nbsp;miles (2.1&nbsp;km) north of PA 118, 0.5&nbsp;miles (0.80&nbsp;km)  south of Waters Meet, and is the first of the falls named by the DCNR encountered when heading north on the Falls Trail.<ref name ="hike pa">Young, pp. 66<U+2013>71.</ref> || [[File:Ricketts Glen State Park Murray Reynolds Falls 6.jpg|200x200px|alt=Water falls through a chute in layered rock, divided by a large pulpit-shaped boulder. A pool is visible at the base of the falls, and the leaves on the surrounding sunlit trees are bright green or yellow.]]
