||R. B. Ricketts || {{nts|36}}&nbsp;feet<br> (11.0&nbsp;m)  || 1,676&nbsp;feet<br> (510&nbsp;m)<ref>{{cite web | work = [[Geographic Names Information System]] | publisher = [[United States Geological Survey]] | date = September 1, 1989 | url ={{Gnis3|1201531}} | title = R B Ricketts Falls | accessdate = November 19, 2009 }}</ref> || {{coord|41|19|27|N|76|16|27|W|name=R B Ricketts Falls}} ||cascade, then cascade || Robert Bruce Ricketts (1839<U+2013>1918) was a colonel in the [[Union Army]] in the [[American Civil War]] who fought at [[Battle of Gettysburg|Gettysburg]]. He owned more than 80,000&nbsp;acres (32,000&nbsp;ha) at one time and sold most of its lumber. Ricketts did preserve the [[old growth forest]] in what became Ricketts Glen State Park, which is named for him. Ricketts named 21 waterfalls on Kitchen Creek and hired six workers to build the original Falls Trail from 1889 to 1893.<ref name = "rgsp"/><ref>Petrillo, p. 49.</ref> The  "exceedingly pleasant" R. B. Ricketts Falls is 0.24&nbsp;miles (0.39&nbsp;km) upstream of Waters Meet, and is the third named falls in Glen Leigh.<ref name = "brown"/> || [[File:Ricketts Glen State Park R. B. Ricketts Falls 4.jpg|200x200px|center|alt=A double cascade falls over several layers of rock at left. A tributary enters the stream from the opposite bank in the form of a smaller waterfall. Conifer saplings are visible on the bank of the creek, which is surrounded by a mixed forest with a variety of autumn colors. The newly fallen leaves cover the rocks on the creek bank and are visible floating in the water.]]
