|| Tuscarora || {{nts|47}}&nbsp;feet<br> (14.3&nbsp;m) || 1,713&nbsp;feet<br> (522&nbsp;m)<ref>{{cite web | work = [[Geographic Names Information System]] | publisher = [[United States Geological Survey]] | date = September 1, 1989 | url ={{Gnis3|1201537}} | title = Tuscarora Falls | accessdate = November 21, 2009 }}</ref> || {{coord|41|19|17|N|76|16|46|W|name=Tuscarora Falls}} || cascade, then falls || Tuscarora Falls is the second named falls in Ganoga Glen, and is a little more than 0.1&nbsp;miles (0.16&nbsp;km) upstream of Waters Meet.<ref name ="young 70"/><ref name = "brown"/> The [[Tuscarora (tribe)|Tuscarora]] are an Iroquoian speaking people who originally lived in what is now [[North Carolina]], then moved to [[New York]]. In 1713 the Tuscarora became the sixth member of the Iroquois Confederation, which then became known as the Six Nations.<ref>Donehoo, pp. 71, 72, 237<U+2013>240.</ref> During the [[American Revolutionary War]], the Tuscarora and their allies the [[Oneida tribe|Oneida]] were the only Iroquois who supported the United States.<ref name="Donehoo, p. 136">Donehoo, p. 136.</ref> ||[[File:Ricketts Glen State Park Tuscarora Falls 4.jpg|200x200px|center|alt=A cascade fall is at the top and below the cascade is a fall split by a rock into two, with a straight drop into a plunge pool. It is autumn, with leaves in various stages of color on the trees; some are green and others are orange or yellow. Fallen leaves cover many of the rocks along the stream.]]
