|| Conestoga || {{nts|17}}&nbsp;feet<br> (5.2&nbsp;m) || 1,824&nbsp;feet<br> (556&nbsp;m)<ref>{{cite web | work = [[Geographic Names Information System]] | publisher = [[United States Geological Survey]] | date = September 1, 1989 | url ={{Gnis3|1201538}} | title = Conestoga Falls | accessdate = November 21, 2009 }}</ref> || {{coord|41|19|16|N|76|16|56|W|name=Conestoga Falls}} || slide || Conestoga Falls is the third named falls in Ganoga Glen, and is 0.3&nbsp;miles (0.48&nbsp;km) upstream of Waters Meet.<ref name ="young 70"/><ref name = "brown"/> The Conestoga or [[Susquehannock]]s were an Iroquoian-speaking people who lived on the [[Susquehanna River]], which is named for them; the park is in the Susquehanna's [[drainage basin]]. After the Iroquois defeated the Susquehannocks in war in 1675, the survivors were [[Cultural assimilation|assimilated]] into other tribes, until the last members were killed by the [[Paxton Boys]] in 1763.<ref>Donehoo, p. 34<U+2013>38.</ref> Brown calls Conestoga Falls "not particularly photogenic".<ref>Brown, p. 60.</ref> ||[[File:Ricketts Glen State Park Conestoga Falls 6.jpg|200x200px|alt=A view of a slide falls, looking down from at or near the top of the falls. It is autumn, with leaves in various stages of color on the trees; some are green and others are orange or yellow. Fallen leaves cover many of the rocks along the stream. The falls are horizontal through the image.]]
