|| Mohican || {{nts|39}}&nbsp;feet<br> (11.9&nbsp;m) || 1,788&nbsp;feet<br> (545&nbsp;m)<ref>{{cite web | work = [[Geographic Names Information System]] | publisher = [[United States Geological Survey]] | date = September 1, 1989 | url ={{Gnis3|1201539}} | title = Mohican Falls | accessdate = November 23, 2009 }}</ref> || {{coord|41|19|18|N|76|16|58|W|name=Mohican Falls}} || slide, then slide || Mohican Falls is the fourth named falls in Ganoga Glen, and is 0.4&nbsp;miles (0.64&nbsp;km) upstream of Waters Meet.<ref name ="young 70"/><ref name = "brown"/> The Mohicans or [[Mahican]]s were an [[Algonquian languages|Algonquian]] speaking people who originally lived on the upper part of the [[Hudson River]]. They lost a prolonged war with the [[Mohawk nation]] and other Iroquois in 1673 and some later lived in Pennsylvania.<ref>Wallace, pp. 18, 103.</ref> Mohican Falls consists of two slides, one above the other. Brown notes it is difficult to photograph both parts (only the top slide is pictured here).<ref name = "brown 61">Brown, p. 61.</ref> ||[[File:Ricketts Glen State Park Mohican Falls 7.jpg|200x200px|alt= A wide slide falls, with a hiking trail on the left. Native stone stairs for the trail ascend the glen. Newly fallen leaves litter the rocks on the edge of the stream.]]
