|| Cayuga || {{nts|11}}&nbsp;feet<br> (3.4&nbsp;m) || 2,041&nbsp;feet<br> (622&nbsp;m)<ref>{{cite web | work = [[Geographic Names Information System]] | publisher = [[United States Geological Survey]] | date = September 1, 1989 | url ={{Gnis3|1201543}} | title = Cayuga Falls | accessdate = November 23, 2009 }}</ref> || {{coord|41|19|31|N|76|17|06|W|name=Cayuga Falls}} || cascade || Cayuga Falls is the eighth named falls in Ganoga Glen, and is 0.8&nbsp;miles (1.3&nbsp;km) upstream of Waters Meet.<ref name ="young 70"/><ref name = "brown"/> According to Brown, Cayuga Falls "just isn't photogenic".<ref name = "brown 63">Brown, p. 63.</ref> The [[Cayuga nation|Cayuga]] are an Iroquoian-speaking people and one of the five original members of the Iroquois; their lands were between the central [[Onondaga (tribe)|Onondaga]] and the easternmost [[Mohawk nation|Mohawk]]. They were "Younger Brothers" in the Iroquois Confederation and were "affiliated with the Mohawks".<ref name = "wallace 90"/> ||[[File:Ricketts Glen State Park Cayuga Falls 2.jpg|200x200px|center|alt= A cascade divided into two parts by a large rock, more water flows on the right side and a large limb has fallen diagonally across the right bank. Moss and ferns line the bank and newly fallen leaves litter the rocks. Ferns and grasses grow on a large boulder in the center of the stream.]]
|-
|| Oneida || {{nts|13}}&nbsp;feet<br> (4.0&nbsp;m) || 2,126&nbsp;feet<br> (648&nbsp;m)<ref>{{cite web | work = [[Geographic Names Information System]] | publisher = [[United States Geological Survey]] | date = September 1, 1989 | url ={{Gnis3|1201544}} | title = Oneida Falls | accessdate = November 23, 2009 }}</ref> || {{coord|41|19|36|N|76|17|14|W|name=Oneida Falls}} || falls || Oneida Falls is the ninth named falls in Ganoga Glen, and is 0.9&nbsp;miles (1.4&nbsp;km) upstream of Waters Meet.<ref name ="young 70"/><ref name = "brown"/> Brown describes the pleasures of photographing this falls.<ref name = "brown 63"/> The [[Oneida nation|Oneida]] are an Iroquoian-speaking people and one of the five original members of the Iroquois; their lands were between the central [[Onondaga (tribe)|Onondaga]] and the westernmost [[Seneca nation|Seneca]]. They were "Younger Brothers" in the Iroquois Confederation and were "affiliated with the Senecas".<ref name = "wallace 90"/> During the [[American Revolutionary War]], the Oneida and their allies the [[Tuscarora (tribe)|Tuscarora]] were the only Iroquois who supported the United States.<ref name="Donehoo, p. 136"/> ||[[File:Ricketts Glen State Park Oneida Falls 1.jpg|200x200px|center|alt= A front-on view of a wide falls. The stream falls as a curtain of water into a plunge pool. It is autumn, with leaves in various stages of color on the trees; some are green and others are orange or yellow.]]
